# Internationalization (i18n)

## Architecture

Two languages: **Spanish (es)** — primary, **English (en)** — secondary.

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `lib/i18n/translations.ts` | `Translations` interface + `es` / `en` objects |
| `lib/i18n/context.tsx` | `I18nProvider` + `useI18n()` hook |
| `lib/i18n/flip-financial-labels.ts` | Flat `Record<string, string>` for financial tables (separate file due to size) |
| `lib/i18n/index.ts` | Re-exports |

Language is stored in `localStorage` (`pdp_lifecycle_language`), defaults to `es`, falls back to browser preference.

## Rule 1: No Hardcoded User-Facing Strings

Every string visible to users MUST come from `useI18n()`. Never write raw text in JSX.

```tsx
// WRONG
<Button>Guardar</Button>
<p>No se encontraron resultados</p>

// CORRECT
const { t } = useI18n();
<Button>{t.common.save}</Button>
<p>{t.supply.kanban.empty}</p>
```

**Exceptions** (do NOT translate):
- Brand names: "Vistral", "PropHero", "Value Hero", "DocuSign"
- Technical identifiers shown to admins: UUIDs, status codes, API paths
- Units: "€", "m²", "%", "kWh"

## Rule 2: Both Languages Required

When adding a new key, you MUST add it in both `es` and `en` objects simultaneously. The `Translations` interface enforces this at the type level — a missing key in either language is a compile error.

```typescript
// In the Translations interface — add the type
propertyDetail: {
  existingKey: string;
  newKey: string;  // ← add here
};

// In the es object — add Spanish value
newKey: "Texto en español",

// In the en object — add English value
newKey: "English text",
```

**Never leave a placeholder like `"TODO"` or copy the Spanish text into the English slot.** If you don't know the English translation, use a clear approximation and add a `// TODO: verify EN translation` comment.

## Rule 3: Key Naming Convention

Keys follow **dot-separated sections** matching domains and UI areas:

```
t.{domain}.{area}.{concept}
```

| Prefix | Scope |
|--------|-------|
| `t.common.*` | Shared across all domains (save, cancel, loading, yes/no) |
| `t.nav.*` | Sidebar and top navigation |
| `t.supply.*` | Supply domain (kanban, property detail, financial estimate) |
| `t.proyecto.*` | Proyecto domain |
| `t.settlement.*` | Settlement domain |
| `t.admin.*` | Admin domain |
| `t.reno.*` | Reno domain |
| `t.userMenu.*` | User menu, settings, password |
| `t.theme.*` / `t.language.*` | Theme and language selectors |

**Rules:**
- Use `camelCase` for keys: `t.supply.kanban.emptyState`, not `t.supply.kanban.empty_state`
- Avoid abbreviations: `description` not `desc`, `button` not `btn`
- Group related keys under a shared parent: `t.supply.form.fieldLabel`, `t.supply.form.fieldPlaceholder`

## Rule 4: Financial Labels Use the Flat Record Pattern

Financial tables use a separate flat `Record<string, string>` in `lib/i18n/flip-financial-labels.ts` because they have hundreds of keys and are accessed by dynamic lookup (not static `t.x.y`).

When adding financial labels:
1. Add to both `FLIP_FINANCIAL_LABELS_EN` and `FLIP_FINANCIAL_LABELS_ES`
2. Use the same key in both records
3. Prefix keys with the table section: `fs_`, `iva_`, `sg_`, `mp_`, `tir_`, `ui_`, `exec_`, `cf_`, `dialog_`

## Rule 5: Cross-Domain Scope

i18n is **not** limited to Supply. It applies to **all domains**:
- Supply, Proyecto, Settlement, Admin, Reno, Sync, Login
- Shared components (`components/ui/`, `components/auth/`, `components/user/`)
- Any new spawned app under `app/(apps)/`

When creating a component in any domain, use `useI18n()`. No domain is exempt.

## Rule 6: Interpolation Pattern

For dynamic values inside translated strings, use placeholder tokens and replace at the call site:

```typescript
// In translations.ts
resultCount: "{count} resultados encontrados",

// In component
t.supply.kanban.resultCount.replace("{count}", String(total))
```

Keep interpolation simple — one or two placeholders max. If a string needs complex logic, break it into multiple keys.

## Rule 7: Adding a New Domain Section

When a new domain or large feature needs translations:

1. Add a new section to the `Translations` interface
2. Add the `es` values
3. Add the `en` values
4. If the section exceeds ~50 keys, consider extracting to a separate file (like `flip-financial-labels.ts`) and importing into `translations.ts`

## Pre-Coding Checklist (i18n)

```
[ ] All user-facing strings use t.section.key — no hardcoded text
[ ] New keys added to BOTH es and en in translations.ts
[ ] Key names follow camelCase and domain prefix convention
[ ] Financial labels (if applicable) added to flip-financial-labels.ts in both EN and ES
[ ] Interpolation uses {placeholder} pattern, not string concatenation
[ ] Component imports useI18n from lib/i18n
```
